Decode CSV - Simple
This tutorial will explain how to decode CSV structure. 
The tutorial uses ffw::Var which is essential in the following examples. You must read Var - JSON-like data structure tutorial first!
Make sure you add finedata into your linker and add the following headers into your project:
#include 
#include 

Source: ../../examples/data/csv_simple.cpp

// Make sure the lines are separated by \n !!!
std::string str =
    "Year,Make,Model,length\n"
    "1997,Ford,E350,2.34\n"
    "2000,Mercury,Cougar,2.38\n";

ffw::Array arr = ffw::decodeCsv(str);
// ffw::Array arr = ffw::decodeCsvFile("file.csv");

if(arr.size() == 0) {
    std::cerr ().size() == 4);

// Returns Mercury
assert(arr[2].getAs()[1].toString() == "Mercury");

// Returns 1997
assert(arr[1].getAs()[0].toInt() == 1997);

Why the following two lines below are equal?
std::cout ()[3].getAs() () 
In the first line, arr is already ffw::Array. However, ffw::Array holds ffw::Var which can hold any c++ data type. We know that ffw::decodeCsv returns array of arrays, so it is safe to explicitly call getAs(). The [3] returns 4th element and getAs() gives us a reference to the float.
The second line does exactly same thing. The ffw::Var contains two [ ] operators, one for integers, one for strings. If you call the operator with an integer, it will assume you are trying to get ffw::Array and it will call getAs() and [int] at the same time for you... it's just for simplicitly. If you would put a string inside the [ ] operator, it will call getAs() which throws std::bad_cast because in this example because we are dealing with arrays only, no objects.

tutorials/data-csv-advanced.html.body:
Decode CSV - Advanced
This tutorial will explain how to decode CSV structure using more advanced method with more control. 
The tutorial uses ffw::Var which is essential in the following examples. You must read Var - JSON-like data structure tutorial first!
Make sure you add finedata into your linker and add the following headers into your project:
#include 
#include 

Source: ../../examples/data/csv_advanced.cpp

ffw::CsvLoader loader;

// First param: file path
// Second param: delimiter (some CSV use ;) default: ,
// Third param: how are string represented? default: "
if(!loader.openFromFile("file.csv", ',', '\"')){
    std::cerr 
You can also use openFromData which acceps a raw string instead. The getRow acceps one parameter, in which if you pass true it will convert all items into their type (integer, float, std::string, bool). If you pass false no conversion is performed and everything is stored in ffw::Array as std::string.
Source: ../../examples/data/csv_advanced.cpp

std::string str = "1999;Chevy;\"Venture \"\"Extended Edition, Very Large\"\"\";;5000.00";
ffw::Array arr = ffw::CsvLoader::tokenize(str, 0, str.size(), true, ';', '\"');

assert(arr.size() == 5);

assert(arr[0].toInt() == 1999);
assert(arr[2].toString() == "Venture \"Extended Edition, Very Large\"");
assert(arr[3].empty() == true);

The function ffw::CsvLoader::tokenize acceps std::string in which you specify the start and the end. Via the 4th parameter you tell it to either decode (true) values into integers, floats, string, etc... or leave everything (false) as std::string. The 5th and 6th specify how are items separated from each other and how are string expressed. Usually in CSV files the items are separated with a comma and strings are enclosed in double quotation marks.

